{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ec10f2d3-8ecf-43a8-b634-79dcfdf90890","content":"Here's my analysis of the evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## MSBuild Evaluation Performance Issues\n\n**1. File I/O property function (High impact)**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions during evaluation is expensive — it blocks the evaluation phase with synchronous I/O. Move this to a target that runs at build-time instead.\n\n**2. Overly broad glob pattern (Medium impact)**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. If this directory grows (dependencies, artifacts, node_modules), evaluation time grows linearly. Use `DefaultItemExcludes` or a more targeted glob.\n\n**3. Deep import chain (Low–Medium impact)**\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nA 3-level chain here is modest, but this pattern doesn't scale. Each import adds evaluation overhead. Flatten or consolidate where possible.\n\n**Recommendations:**\n- Replace the `File::ReadAllText` property with a target using `ReadLinesFromFile` that runs `BeforeTargets=\"Build\"`.\n- Narrow the glob to specific extensions (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n- Consider merging the import chain into fewer files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a9a28cf1-9c1c-4b69-8dde-59ffb1a29e57","outputTokens":363,"requestId":"5C08:1CFDE0:1ED06DD:22AE9AD:6A07CA27"},"id":"cd953006-3e01-4d18-820e-5ac9d5ec0c29","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:36:49.122Z","parentId":"6751fbb5-0c9c-4837-9d01-207f1bf0ffd7"}
